WEBVTT

1
00:01:30.600 --> 00:01:33.260
Quick! We can't
hold him back much longer.

2
00:01:36.537 --> 00:01:37.748
Hurry!

3
00:01:41.141 --> 00:01:42.469
Come on!

4
00:01:50.512 --> 00:01:51.509
Quick!

5
00:01:56.563 --> 00:01:57.666
Faster!

6
00:02:10.782 --> 00:02:12.488
Up on the balcony!
Come on! Quickly!

7
00:02:40.499 --> 00:02:43.414
Just read them
the sentence!

8
00:02:46.259 --> 00:02:48.229
The sentence of the court...

9
00:02:48.555 --> 00:02:50.446
is that in two days hence...

10
00:02:50.964 --> 00:02:55.172
the perfumer journeyman:
Jean-Baptiste Grenouille...

11
00:02:55.782 --> 00:02:58.119
shall be bound
to a wooden cross...

12
00:02:58.317 --> 00:03:01.470
with his face raised
towards heaven!

13
00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:05.191
And whilst still alive...

14
00:03:05.728 --> 00:03:09.591
be dealt twelve blows
with an iron rod...

15
00:03:12.002 --> 00:03:14.942
breaking the joints
of his arms...

16
00:03:16.189 --> 00:03:17.140
his shoulders...

17
00:03:17.934 --> 00:03:19.322
his hips...

18
00:03:20.070 --> 00:03:21.811
his legs!

19
00:03:23.097 --> 00:03:27.332
He shall then be raised up
to hang until dead.

20
00:03:27.868 --> 00:03:31.164
And all customary acts of mercy...

21
00:03:31.276 --> 00:03:34.311
are expressly forbidden
the executioner.

22
00:03:43.324 --> 00:03:45.617
In 18th century France...

23
00:03:45.722 --> 00:03:51.881
there lived a man who was one of the most gifted
and notorious personages of his time.

24
00:03:52.342 --> 00:03:55.387
His name was
Jean-Baptiste Grenouille.

25
00:03:56.118 --> 00:04:00.392
And if his name has been forgotten today,
it is for the sole reason...

26
00:04:00.435 --> 00:04:03.433
that his entire ambition
was restricted to a domain...

27
00:04:03.538 --> 00:04:07.343
that leaves no trace in history:

28
00:04:10.709 --> 00:04:13.953
to the fleeting realm of scent.

29
00:04:13.954 --> 00:04:19.764
PERFUME
The Story of a Murderer

30
00:04:27.728 --> 00:04:29.788
In the period of which we speak...

31
00:04:29.895 --> 00:04:35.648
there reigned in the cities a stench
barely conceivable to us modern men and women.

32
00:04:36.769 --> 00:04:39.869
Naturally, the stench
was foulest in Paris...

33
00:04:39.906 --> 00:04:42.974
for Paris was
the largest city in Europe.

34
00:04:43.443 --> 00:04:46.863
And nowhere in Paris was that stench
more profoundly repugnant...

35
00:04:46.968 --> 00:04:49.245
than in the city's fish market.

36
00:04:50.876 --> 00:04:54.296
Here we are.
I'll get another box.

37
00:04:55.009 --> 00:04:59.147
It was here then,
on the most putrid spot in the whole kingdom...

38
00:04:59.301 --> 00:05:01.882
that Jean-Baptiste Grenouille was born...

39
00:05:01.885 --> 00:05:04.797
on the 17th of July, 1738.

40
00:05:29.143 --> 00:05:31.117
It was his mother's fifth birth.

41
00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:34.286
She delivered them all here
under her fish stand.

42
00:05:34.395 --> 00:05:37.050
And all had been stillbirths,
or semi-stillbirths.

43
00:05:37.231 --> 00:05:38.275
Are you alright?

44
00:05:39.266 --> 00:05:41.892
And by evening, the whole mess
had been shoveled away...

45
00:05:41.965 --> 00:05:43.759
with the fish guts
into the river.

46
00:05:44.543 --> 00:05:46.521
It would be much the same today...

47
00:05:47.343 --> 00:05:48.823
but then...

48
00:05:49.436 --> 00:05:52.369
Jean-Baptiste chose differently.

49
00:06:26.186 --> 00:06:27.390
What's that noise?

50
00:06:28.047 --> 00:06:29.926
It's... it's a baby.

51
00:06:29.927 --> 00:06:31.288
What's going on here?

52
00:06:35.289 --> 00:06:38.192
- It's a newborn.
- Where's his mother?

53
00:06:39.704 --> 00:06:40.963
She was just here.

54
00:06:43.543 --> 00:06:48.940
She tried to kill it, her own child.
She tried to kill a baby!

55
00:06:50.836 --> 00:06:52.501
There! There she is!

56
00:06:52.763 --> 00:06:55.334
- Stop! Stop where you are!
- Murderer!

57
00:06:55.422 --> 00:06:59.100
Thus, the first sound
to escape Grenouille's lips...

58
00:06:59.709 --> 00:07:01.457
sent his mother
to the gallows.

59
00:07:05.414 --> 00:07:08.072
And Jean-Baptiste,
by official order...

60
00:07:09.001 --> 00:07:11.386
to the orphange
of Madame Gaillard.

61
00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:19.792
- How many today?
- Four, well... three and a half.

62
00:07:23.908 --> 00:07:29.538
- As usual, more dead than alive.
- Just take the money and sign!

63
00:07:36.762 --> 00:07:40.517
- Make room!
- Where?

64
00:07:40.555 --> 00:07:41.498
Move!

65
00:07:56.593 --> 00:07:57.914
Is he dead?

66
00:08:24.937 --> 00:08:28.648
- That's not staying in my bed.
- Let's throw it out then.

67
00:08:28.851 --> 00:08:32.685
- What if it screams?
- It's just a kiddie.

68
00:08:51.820 --> 00:08:54.065
Harder! Push!

69
00:08:55.489 --> 00:08:57.781
What are you doing?

70
00:09:06.097 --> 00:09:06.998
For Madame Gaillard...

71
00:09:07.077 --> 00:09:10.249
Grenouille was a source of income
just like any other.

72
00:09:11.011 --> 00:09:16.891
The children, however, sensed at once
that there was something different about him.

73
00:09:33.469 --> 00:09:38.039
By the age of five, Jean-Baptiste
still could not talk.

74
00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:43.810
But he had been born with a talent
that made him unique among their kind.

75
00:10:46.797 --> 00:10:49.401
It was not that the other children
hated him...

76
00:10:50.228 --> 00:10:53.123
they felt unnerved
by him.

77
00:10:57.136 --> 00:11:01.304
Increasingly, he became aware
that his phenomenal sense of smell...

78
00:11:01.401 --> 00:11:03.852
was a gift that had been give to him...

79
00:11:04.244 --> 00:11:05.901
and him alone.

80
00:11:14.258 --> 00:11:17.713
When Jean-Baptiste did
finally learn to speak...

81
00:11:17.984 --> 00:11:20.130
he soon found
that everyday language...

82
00:11:20.307 --> 00:11:25.542
proved inadequate for all the olfactory experience
he's accumulating within himself.

83
00:11:29.946 --> 00:11:31.431
Wood.

84
00:11:37.364 --> 00:11:38.714
Warm wood.

85
00:11:40.091 --> 00:11:43.973
Grass... wet grass.

86
00:11:44.873 --> 00:11:48.352
Stones... warm stones.

87
00:11:51.283 --> 00:11:55.713
Water... cold water.

88
00:12:02.276 --> 00:12:03.480
Frog.

89
00:12:06.017 --> 00:12:07.855
Wet stones.

90
00:12:08.515 --> 00:12:12.219
Big wet frog stones.

91
00:12:13.856 --> 00:12:15.454
Something...

92
00:12:17.447 --> 00:12:20.496
something, something.

93
00:12:21.999 --> 00:12:26.868
By the age of thirteen, Madame Gaillard
no longer had room for Jean-Baptiste...

94
00:12:27.228 --> 00:12:28.755
and therefore decided
to sell him.

95
00:12:28.756 --> 00:12:29.966
Come on!

96
00:12:33.248 --> 00:12:34.412
Ten francs.

97
00:12:36.384 --> 00:12:39.613
From his first breath
of the odor enveloping this man...

98
00:12:39.801 --> 00:12:41.866
Seven, it's not worth so much.

99
00:12:42.196 --> 00:12:45.266
Grenouille knew that his life
in Grimal's tannery...

100
00:12:45.461 --> 00:12:46.987
would be worth precisely
as much...

101
00:12:47.114 --> 00:12:48.904
as the work
he could accomplish.

102
00:12:52.452 --> 00:12:54.319
Unfortunately for Madame Gaillard...

103
00:12:57.994 --> 00:13:00.846
the bargain was short-lived.

104
00:13:06.945 --> 00:13:10.468
Life expectancy in the tannery
was a mere five years.

105
00:13:11.112 --> 00:13:15.062
But Jean-Baptiste proved to be
as tough as a resilient bacterium.

106
00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:17.651
He adjusted to
his new fate...

107
00:13:17.652 --> 00:13:20.791
and became a paragon
of docility and diligence...

108
00:13:21.108 --> 00:13:25.261
slaved 15, 16 hours a day,
summer and winter.

109
00:13:26.713 --> 00:13:31.233
Gradually, he became aware
of a world beyond the tannery...

110
00:13:32.263 --> 00:13:36.805
where utopia of unexplored smells
lay in store for him.

111
00:14:01.271 --> 00:14:02.363
Grenouille.

112
00:14:06.482 --> 00:14:09.649
Come with us.
I'm taking you to town for delivery.

113
00:14:10.730 --> 00:14:15.186
Jean-Baptiste Grenouille
had triumphed. He was alive.

114
00:14:16.053 --> 00:14:19.172
And at last, he was in his element.

115
00:14:58.660 --> 00:15:00.242
He was not choosing.

116
00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:03.647
He did not differentiate between
what is commonly considered to be...

117
00:15:03.696 --> 00:15:05.796
good smells from bad.

118
00:15:07.199 --> 00:15:10.072
At least, not yet.

119
00:15:12.438 --> 00:15:14.601
He was very greedy.

120
00:15:15.058 --> 00:15:16.998
The goal was to possess...

121
00:15:17.057 --> 00:15:20.571
everything the world had to offer
in the way of odors.

122
00:15:21.334 --> 00:15:25.455
His only condition being...
that they were new ones.

123
00:15:28.145 --> 00:15:31.911
Thousands upon thousands of odors
formed an invisible gruel...

124
00:15:32.058 --> 00:15:36.463
which he dissected into its
smallest and most remote parts of pieces.

125
00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:54.580
Grenouille!

126
00:15:58.537 --> 00:16:00.067
Come on!

127
00:16:04.045 --> 00:16:05.785
Your ass over here.

128
00:17:20.131 --> 00:17:23.421
- What is it called?
- "Amor and Psyche", madame.

129
00:17:23.740 --> 00:17:25.332
My little creation.

130
00:17:25.910 --> 00:17:30.172
- May I try it?
- If you allow me, mademoiselle.

131
00:17:37.887 --> 00:17:40.405
Sheer heaven...

132
00:17:43.005 --> 00:17:47.068
Monsieur P¨¦lissier, you are
truly an artiste.

133
00:20:15.916 --> 00:20:17.183
What do you want?

134
00:20:26.312 --> 00:20:27.568
Want to buy some?

135
00:20:41.453 --> 00:20:42.777
Two for a sou.

136
00:26:55.717 --> 00:26:57.501
That's for you
running off like that.

137
00:26:58.311 --> 00:26:59.529
I'll kill you!

138
00:27:03.353 --> 00:27:06.182
That night, he could not sleep.

139
00:27:07.086 --> 00:27:11.742
The intoxicating power of the girls's scent
suddenly made it clear to him...

140
00:27:11.798 --> 00:27:16.123
why he had come to his own life
so tenaciously, so savagely.

141
00:27:17.796 --> 00:27:19.137
The meaning and purpose...

142
00:27:19.232 --> 00:27:22.262
of his miserable existence
had a higher destiny.

143
00:27:23.644 --> 00:27:26.523
He would learn
how to preserve scent...

144
00:27:26.747 --> 00:27:31.106
so that never again would he lose
such sublime beauty.

145
00:27:55.306 --> 00:27:58.991
There were about a dozen perfumers
in Paris in those days.

146
00:28:00.049 --> 00:28:04.583
One of them, the one celebrated
Italian perfumer, Giuseppe Baldini,

147
00:28:04.677 --> 00:28:06.756
had set up shop
in the center of the bridge,

148
00:28:06.825 --> 00:28:11.395
called "the Pont au Change" on his arrival
in Paris over thirty years ago.

149
00:28:12.142 --> 00:28:14.850
To be sure,
at one time in his youth,

150
00:28:15.036 --> 00:28:20.204
Baldini had created several truly great perfumes
to which he owed his fortune.

151
00:28:22.038 --> 00:28:26.728
But now, Baldini was out of touch,
out of fashion,

152
00:28:26.954 --> 00:28:31.087
and spent his days
waiting for customers that no longer came.

153
00:28:32.891 --> 00:28:34.852
- Ch¨¦nier! There you are!
- Monsieur Baldini.

154
00:28:34.853 --> 00:28:36.213
Put on your wig.

155
00:28:36.813 --> 00:28:38.289
Put on your wig!

156
00:28:40.748 --> 00:28:41.752
You going out?

157
00:28:42.581 --> 00:28:44.707
I will retire to my study
for a few hours,

158
00:28:44.909 --> 00:28:47.529
and do not want to be disturbed
under any circumstances.

159
00:28:47.637 --> 00:28:49.737
Will you be creating
a new perfume, Monsieur Baldini?

160
00:28:49.832 --> 00:28:52.132
Correct.
For Count Verhamont.

161
00:28:52.663 --> 00:28:55.092
He's asked for something like...

162
00:28:55.147 --> 00:28:59.206
I think he said it was called...
"Amor and Psyche"?

163
00:28:59.603 --> 00:29:01.959
That swindler in the
rue Saint-Andr¨¦-des-Arts.

164
00:29:02.313 --> 00:29:05.700
- P¨¦lissier.
- P¨¦lissier! That's him.

165
00:29:07.319 --> 00:29:08.709
"Amor and Psyche"ê.

166
00:29:13.645 --> 00:29:15.672
- Do you know it?
- Oh, yes.

167
00:29:15.759 --> 00:29:17.840
You can smell it everywhere
these days, monsieur.

168
00:29:18.795 --> 00:29:20.156
Every street corner.

169
00:29:21.714 --> 00:29:25.124
In fact, I just purchased
you a sample.

170
00:29:27.084 --> 00:29:28.867
In case you wanted
to test it.

171
00:29:31.436 --> 00:29:34.757
What on earth makes you think
I'd be interested in testing it?

172
00:29:36.517 --> 00:29:38.936
You're right.
It's nothing special.

173
00:29:39.576 --> 00:29:42.366
Actually, it's a very
common scent.

174
00:29:43.087 --> 00:29:46.136
I believe the head cord
contains lime oil.

175
00:29:47.911 --> 00:29:51.241
Really? And the heart cord?

176
00:29:51.921 --> 00:29:54.276
Orange blossom, I believe.

177
00:29:54.830 --> 00:29:59.352
And civet in the base cord,
but I cannot say for sure.

178
00:29:59.522 --> 00:30:03.388
Well, I couldn't care less what that bungler
P¨¦lissier slops into his perfumes.

179
00:30:03.761 --> 00:30:05.077
Naturally not, monsieur.

180
00:30:05.625 --> 00:30:08.987
And I am thinking of creating something
for Count Verhamont...

181
00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:12.775
that will cause
a veritable sensation.

182
00:30:13.099 --> 00:30:14.948
I'm sure it will, Monsieur Baldini.

183
00:30:16.086 --> 00:30:20.258
Take charge of the shop, Ch¨¦nier.
And don't let anyone come near me.

184
00:30:20.378 --> 00:30:23.515
Inspiration requires
peace and tranquility.

185
00:30:24.686 --> 00:30:27.616
Vanessa! Bring me the handkerchiefs!

186
00:30:58.227 --> 00:30:59.693
Here are your handkerchiefs.

187
00:30:59.826 --> 00:31:02.530
Grazie... grazie... grazie!

188
00:31:05.434 --> 00:31:07.410
Is there anything else
you need?

189
00:31:08.389 --> 00:31:10.290
Inspiration, perhaps.

190
00:31:10.563 --> 00:31:12.012
Come on, Giuseppe!

191
00:31:14.432 --> 00:31:17.560
You're still
the great perfumer Baldini.

192
00:32:11.282 --> 00:32:14.252
Bellissimo...
Wonderful...

193
00:32:18.345 --> 00:32:20.088
He did it again.

194
00:32:26.339 --> 00:32:29.508
Lime oil, yes indeed.

195
00:32:32.657 --> 00:32:35.838
Orange blossom, to be sure.

196
00:32:40.096 --> 00:32:42.193
And a hint of cloves, perhaps.

197
00:32:44.408 --> 00:32:45.511
No...

198
00:32:47.165 --> 00:32:48.744
Well, could be cinnamon.

199
00:32:51.205 --> 00:32:52.072
It's gone.

200
00:32:55.848 --> 00:32:57.027
Cinnamon.

201
00:32:57.951 --> 00:32:59.380
It's not cinnamon...

202
00:33:03.441 --> 00:33:04.430
Cloves.

203
00:33:04.961 --> 00:33:05.442
No...

204
00:33:06.403 --> 00:33:07.420
Musk?

205
00:33:07.637 --> 00:33:08.638
No.

206
00:33:49.329 --> 00:33:50.105
Who's there?

207
00:33:50.868 --> 00:33:52.411
I'm from Grimal's tannery.

208
00:33:56.141 --> 00:33:58.187
I've brought
the goatskins you ordered.

209
00:34:04.116 --> 00:34:05.356
Follow me.

210
00:34:11.650 --> 00:34:12.888
This way.

211
00:34:47.138 --> 00:34:49.978
There. Leave them there.

212
00:34:59.247 --> 00:35:01.037
Tell your master
the skins are fine.

213
00:35:01.579 --> 00:35:03.935
I'll come by the next few days
and pay for them.

214
00:35:05.133 --> 00:35:06.562
Yes, monsieur.

215
00:35:12.936 --> 00:35:15.944
You want to make this leather
smell good, don't you?

216
00:35:17.374 --> 00:35:22.703
- Why, of course.
- With "Amor and Psyche" by P¨¦lissier?

217
00:35:26.670 --> 00:35:30.747
Whatever gave you the absurb idea
I would use someone else's perfume?

218
00:35:31.931 --> 00:35:32.794
It's all over you.

219
00:35:33.285 --> 00:35:35.647
It's on your forehead,
your nose, your hands.

220
00:35:35.661 --> 00:35:40.665
It's bad, "Amor and Psyche" is, master.
There's too much rosemary in it, and too much of...

221
00:35:42.401 --> 00:35:44.637
that and that.

222
00:35:47.419 --> 00:35:51.062
Bergamot and patchouli.

223
00:35:51.120 --> 00:35:52.173
Pa...

224
00:35:53.026 --> 00:35:55.605
- Patchouli.
- Patchou...

225
00:36:00.906 --> 00:36:02.149
What else?

226
00:36:05.282 --> 00:36:06.820
That and that.

227
00:36:08.757 --> 00:36:10.027
That and that.

228
00:36:19.578 --> 00:36:21.077
Orange blossom.

229
00:36:22.727 --> 00:36:23.864
Lime.

230
00:36:25.254 --> 00:36:26.686
- Musk.
- Musk.

231
00:36:29.923 --> 00:36:31.570
And cloves.

232
00:36:31.898 --> 00:36:33.470
And this.

233
00:36:41.955 --> 00:36:44.794
- Storax?
- That's in it too.

234
00:36:44.871 --> 00:36:47.792
- Storax. Storax.
- Storax. Storax.

235
00:36:54.508 --> 00:36:57.267
You have, it appears,
a fine nose, young man. But...

236
00:36:57.328 --> 00:37:01.300
My nose knows all the smells in the world.
It's the best nose in Paris.

237
00:37:01.495 --> 00:37:03.843
Only I don't know the names.
I need to learn the names...

238
00:37:03.877 --> 00:37:05.775
- learn them all...
- No! No! No! Basta!

239
00:37:05.849 --> 00:37:07.677
You don't interrupt me when I'm speaking.

240
00:37:07.726 --> 00:37:10.073
You're both impertinent
and insolent!

241
00:37:11.073 --> 00:37:13.477
Even I don't know every scent.

242
00:37:15.707 --> 00:37:19.129
I, of course, know for some time
the ingredients of "Amor and Psyche".

243
00:37:19.130 --> 00:37:23.233
But all it needs to find that out
is a passably fine nose, nothing else.

244
00:37:25.294 --> 00:37:28.647
But it needs the craft
of a true perfumer...

245
00:37:29.513 --> 00:37:31.382
to detect the exact formula.

246
00:37:31.838 --> 00:37:36.425
Which notes, which cords.
And in what precise measurements.

247
00:37:37.899 --> 00:37:41.021
Could you tell me the exact formula
of "Amor and Psyche"ê?

248
00:37:43.795 --> 00:37:45.470
"Best nose in Paris".

249
00:37:51.020 --> 00:37:52.425
Speak up!

250
00:37:53.347 --> 00:37:56.540
You see, you can't, can you?
And I'll tell you why.

251
00:37:57.842 --> 00:38:00.485
Because talent means
next to nothing!

252
00:38:02.713 --> 00:38:05.319
While experience, acquired in humility...

253
00:38:05.852 --> 00:38:09.267
and hard work, means everything.

254
00:38:13.706 --> 00:38:16.283
I don't, I don't know
what a formula is.

255
00:38:16.493 --> 00:38:19.443
But I can make
"Amor and Psyche" for you now.

256
00:38:20.787 --> 00:38:23.991
And you think I'll just let you
slop around in my laboratory...

257
00:38:24.097 --> 00:38:26.072
with essential oils
that are worth a fortune?

258
00:38:26.422 --> 00:38:27.372
You?

259
00:38:28.525 --> 00:38:31.044
- Yes.
- Now pay attention!

260
00:38:34.434 --> 00:38:35.902
What is your name, anyway?

261
00:38:37.941 --> 00:38:39.695
Jean-Baptiste Grenouille.

262
00:38:42.570 --> 00:38:45.039
Very well, Jean-Baptiste Grenouille.

263
00:38:46.867 --> 00:38:50.282
You shall have the opportunity now,
this very moment, to prove your assertion.

264
00:38:50.338 --> 00:38:53.505
Your grandiose failure will also be
an opportunity for you to learn...

265
00:38:53.553 --> 00:38:56.879
- the virture of humility.
- How much do you want me to make?

266
00:38:56.932 --> 00:39:00.465
- How much of... what?
- How much "Amor and Psyche" do you want?

267
00:39:03.283 --> 00:39:07.275
- Shall I fill this flask?
- No! You shall not!

268
00:39:16.635 --> 00:39:19.308
- You may fill this one.
- Yes, master.

269
00:39:22.352 --> 00:39:24.572
- But, Master Baldini,
- Hmm?

270
00:39:24.930 --> 00:39:27.602
you must let me do it
in my own way.

271
00:39:28.071 --> 00:39:29.914
As you please.

272
00:39:36.411 --> 00:39:38.746
Don't drop that!
That's pure alcohol!

273
00:39:38.821 --> 00:39:41.054
You want to blow up
the entire building?

274
00:39:43.601 --> 00:39:45.300
You have to measure it first!

275
00:40:34.322 --> 00:40:37.776
Stop! Stop it!
That's enough! Basta!

276
00:40:38.176 --> 00:40:39.463
You know nothing!

277
00:40:39.955 --> 00:40:44.646
Essential oils are always to be
mixed first, then the alcohol added.

278
00:40:44.703 --> 00:40:47.963
And never ever let this perfume
to be shaken like that.

279
00:40:48.261 --> 00:40:51.583
I must've been insane
to listen to your asinine gibberish.

280
00:40:53.520 --> 00:40:55.146
Yes, we're done.

281
00:41:25.001 --> 00:41:26.700
Mamamiya...

282
00:41:41.110 --> 00:41:43.436
This is "Amor and Psyche".

283
00:41:44.277 --> 00:41:46.626
But it's not a good perfume, master.

284
00:41:48.205 --> 00:41:51.701
If you let me again, master,
I'll make it more better.

285
00:43:06.771 --> 00:43:09.006
That's a really good perfume.

286
00:43:15.910 --> 00:43:18.109
Don't you want
to smell it, master?

287
00:43:18.162 --> 00:43:19.993
I'm not in the mood
to test it now.

288
00:43:20.044 --> 00:43:22.852
I have other things
on my mind. Go now.

289
00:43:24.719 --> 00:43:27.252
- But, master...
- Go now!

290
00:43:42.518 --> 00:43:45.541
Can't I come to work
for you, master, can't I?

291
00:43:47.744 --> 00:43:49.895
- Let me think about it.
- Master!

292
00:43:51.577 --> 00:43:54.709
I have to learn
how to keep smell.

293
00:43:56.199 --> 00:44:00.597
- What?
- Can you teach me that?

294
00:44:01.136 --> 00:44:03.412
I shall have to think
about it. Now go.

295
00:44:49.811 --> 00:44:51.390
I love you.

296
00:44:57.930 --> 00:45:00.467
I'll give you 50 francs for him.

297
00:45:07.821 --> 00:45:09.447
Grenouille!

298
00:45:09.491 --> 00:45:13.350
Grimal's transaction had
a profound effect on all three parties.

299
00:45:13.411 --> 00:45:14.475
Hey, watch out!

300
00:45:18.197 --> 00:45:21.315
Now at least, upon
Monsieur Grimal himself.

301
00:45:24.194 --> 00:45:25.968
As for Giuseppe Baldini,

302
00:45:26.039 --> 00:45:30.755
the acquisition of Grenouille miraculously
transformed his dwindling business,

303
00:45:30.823 --> 00:45:33.771
even surpassing
its former glory.

304
00:45:41.825 --> 00:45:43.969
While at last, for Jean-Baptiste,

305
00:45:44.296 --> 00:45:49.062
the mysterious secret
of the perfumers' craft began to unfold.

306
00:45:55.433 --> 00:45:58.020
Now, pay careful attention
to what I tell you.

307
00:45:58.072 --> 00:45:59.603
Just like a musical cord,

308
00:45:59.664 --> 00:46:03.578
a perfume cord contains
four essences, or notes,

309
00:46:03.639 --> 00:46:06.900
carefully selected
for their harmonic affinity.

310
00:46:06.959 --> 00:46:12.427
Each perfume contains three cords:
the head, the heart and the base,

311
00:46:12.465 --> 00:46:15.124
necessitating twelve notes in all.

312
00:46:15.745 --> 00:46:18.771
The head cord contains
the first impression,

313
00:46:18.831 --> 00:46:22.443
lasting only a few minutes,
before giving way to the heart cord:

314
00:46:22.504 --> 00:46:26.255
the theme of the perfume,
lasting several hours.

315
00:46:26.294 --> 00:46:29.029
Finally, the base cord:

316
00:46:29.362 --> 00:46:33.211
the trail of the perfume,
lasting several days.

317
00:46:37.614 --> 00:46:42.587
Mind you, the ancient Egyptians believed
that one can only create a truly original perfume...

318
00:46:42.655 --> 00:46:49.297
by adding an extra note,
one final essence that will ring out...

319
00:46:49.808 --> 00:46:52.058
and dominate the others.

320
00:46:54.329 --> 00:46:58.919
Legend has it that a jar
was once found in a pharaoh's tomb.

321
00:46:59.024 --> 00:47:02.697
And when it was opened,
a perfume was released.

322
00:47:02.822 --> 00:47:05.846
After all those thousands of years,

323
00:47:05.909 --> 00:47:09.982
a perfume of such subtle beauty,
and yet such power,

324
00:47:10.076 --> 00:47:13.017
that for one single moment,

325
00:47:13.075 --> 00:47:17.686
every single person on earth
believed they were in paradise.

326
00:47:19.376 --> 00:47:22.176
Twelve essences
could be identified.

327
00:47:23.201 --> 00:47:27.056
But the thirteenth,
the vital one...

328
00:47:28.577 --> 00:47:30.762
could never be determined.

329
00:47:32.548 --> 00:47:33.396
Why not?

330
00:47:35.905 --> 00:47:36.511
Why not?

331
00:47:36.743 --> 00:47:38.342
What do you mean why not?

332
00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:42.155
Because it's a legend, numskull.

333
00:47:43.443 --> 00:47:44.646
What's a legend?

334
00:47:47.327 --> 00:47:48.283
Never mind.

335
00:48:30.595 --> 00:48:33.136
Jean-Baptiste. Jean-Baptiste.

336
00:48:38.997 --> 00:48:40.283
What's the matter?

337
00:48:40.861 --> 00:48:44.796
I... I have to learn
how to capture a scent.

338
00:48:47.475 --> 00:48:48.985
What are you talking about?

339
00:48:49.502 --> 00:48:54.255
I have to learn how... how to
capture a scent and "reprose" it forever.

340
00:48:54.511 --> 00:48:57.651
- You mean "preserve".
- Yes, teach me that.

341
00:48:58.017 --> 00:49:01.553
Calm down, my boy.
Calm down.

342
00:49:02.137 --> 00:49:03.744
We have work to do.

343
00:49:05.510 --> 00:49:10.914
The soul of beings is their scent.
You said that, master.

344
00:49:12.280 --> 00:49:13.202
Did I?

345
00:49:13.675 --> 00:49:17.700
I will make as many perfumes as you want.
But you have to teach me...

346
00:49:17.967 --> 00:49:20.655
how to capture
the smell of all things.

347
00:49:22.080 --> 00:49:23.456
Can you do that?

348
00:49:24.857 --> 00:49:29.374
- Well, naturally.
- Then teach me everything you know.

349
00:49:32.705 --> 00:49:35.258
And I'll make you the best perfumer
in the whole world.

350
00:49:53.161 --> 00:49:55.110
Imagine, Jean-Baptiste:

351
00:49:55.170 --> 00:50:01.799
ten thousand roses to produce
one single ounce of essential oil.

352
00:50:03.635 --> 00:50:09.774
Now, keep them flowing,
for the bottom petals will be given to stew,

353
00:50:10.022 --> 00:50:11.679
while I set up the alembic.

354
00:50:11.725 --> 00:50:13.593
And take care.
Not to damage them.

355
00:50:13.864 --> 00:50:17.755
We have to let them go to
their deaths with their scent intact.

356
00:50:36.285 --> 00:50:39.781
Perfect! Now, help me
with the boiler set.

357
00:50:53.174 --> 00:50:56.625
Temperature is vital.
When the quicksilver is here,

358
00:50:56.705 --> 00:51:01.600
the heat is precisely correct,
and the oil will gradually rise.

359
00:51:03.006 --> 00:51:08.596
Note that this mechanism is
a remarkable invention of my own devising.

360
00:51:09.163 --> 00:51:15.072
You will observe how cold water
is pumped through here,

361
00:51:15.729 --> 00:51:20.786
allowing the essence
to condense here...

362
00:51:20.844 --> 00:51:22.788
until it finally...

363
00:51:24.002 --> 00:51:25.354
appears...

364
00:51:26.894 --> 00:51:28.202
here!

365
00:51:29.182 --> 00:51:35.543
Of course, out on the hillside above Grasse,
we had only to bellow pure fresh air.

366
00:51:36.589 --> 00:51:39.711
Ah, Grasse! What a town.

367
00:51:41.765 --> 00:51:47.417
The Rome of scents.
The Promised Land of perfume.

368
00:51:48.818 --> 00:51:53.335
No man can rightly
call himself a perfumer,

369
00:51:53.696 --> 00:51:58.057
unless he has proved his worth
in that hallowed place.

370
00:52:00.490 --> 00:52:03.207
Not to worry!
It happens all the time.

371
00:52:04.848 --> 00:52:06.556
To Grasse.

372
00:52:24.524 --> 00:52:25.621
Master.

373
00:52:26.852 --> 00:52:27.867
Look.

374
00:52:33.289 --> 00:52:35.760
The very soul of the rose.

375
00:53:29.962 --> 00:53:31.681
Jean-Baptiste.

376
00:53:34.643 --> 00:53:35.663
What's wrong?

377
00:53:37.155 --> 00:53:38.587
Jean-Baptiste.

378
00:53:41.749 --> 00:53:44.654
- What have you done?
- You lied.

379
00:53:45.006 --> 00:53:48.242
- What?
- You lied to me.

380
00:53:48.873 --> 00:53:51.746
How dare you
talk to me like that!

381
00:53:53.217 --> 00:53:55.935
You said I could capture
the scent of anything.

382
00:53:56.740 --> 00:53:58.185
And so you can!

383
00:54:02.233 --> 00:54:03.479
What do you smell?

384
00:54:04.721 --> 00:54:06.179
What do you smell?

385
00:54:11.622 --> 00:54:12.330
Nothing.

386
00:54:15.877 --> 00:54:19.339
- What were you expecting to smell?
- Glass.

387
00:54:20.055 --> 00:54:24.134
- But glass doesn't smell.
- Of course it does. What's this?

388
00:54:29.407 --> 00:54:30.986
I don't smell a thing.

389
00:54:31.843 --> 00:54:32.564
Basta!

390
00:54:32.618 --> 00:54:35.006
- Did you smell that copper?
- Enough!

391
00:54:38.108 --> 00:54:41.698
You were trying to distil
the smell of copper?

392
00:54:42.219 --> 00:54:43.091
iron...

393
00:54:43.146 --> 00:54:44.152
glass...

394
00:54:44.635 --> 00:54:45.951
copper...

395
00:54:49.613 --> 00:54:51.331
What else did you try?

396
00:54:55.252 --> 00:54:56.041
No!

397
00:54:58.324 --> 00:55:00.354
Have you gone completely insane?!

398
00:55:01.339 --> 00:55:03.465
You told me I had to experiment.

399
00:55:03.752 --> 00:55:08.946
Experiment? Experiment?
With a cat?!

400
00:55:12.151 --> 00:55:14.056
What kind of a human being are youê é?

401
00:55:14.696 --> 00:55:16.319
Don't you know anything?

402
00:55:16.661 --> 00:55:18.900
You can no more distil
the scent of a cat...

403
00:55:18.956 --> 00:55:21.464
than you can distil
the scent of you and me!

404
00:55:32.429 --> 00:55:35.326
- I can't?
- Of course not!

405
00:55:42.571 --> 00:55:44.263
He's in stadio ultimo.

406
00:55:44.320 --> 00:55:45.836
- What?
- He's dying.

407
00:55:45.894 --> 00:55:47.452
Is there nothing you can do?

408
00:55:48.002 --> 00:55:51.188
- I fear not.
- No! He cannot die.

409
00:55:51.247 --> 00:55:55.315
- Well, the fee is 50 francs.
- 50 francs? You're a charlatan!

410
00:56:01.298 --> 00:56:05.469
Oh dear, Jean-Baptiste!

411
00:56:06.597 --> 00:56:10.835
You cannot do this to me.
Please, don't die on me.

412
00:56:11.185 --> 00:56:13.511
Not now, not yet!

413
00:56:24.970 --> 00:56:27.257
Is there...

414
00:56:31.055 --> 00:56:33.083
any other way...

415
00:56:34.434 --> 00:56:37.375
to preserve smell
besides distil it?

416
00:56:37.790 --> 00:56:39.609
Jean-Baptiste...

417
00:56:44.579 --> 00:56:50.713
- Is there, master?
- Well, yes, I... I believe there is.

418
00:56:52.183 --> 00:56:54.143
What is ité?

419
00:56:55.974 --> 00:57:00.101
It is known as
the mysterious art of Enfleurage.

420
00:57:02.594 --> 00:57:04.277
Can you teach me?

421
00:57:07.416 --> 00:57:10.742
Not even I am intimate
with the secrets.

422
00:57:13.513 --> 00:57:16.032
But could I learn it in Grasse?

423
00:57:17.186 --> 00:57:20.051
- Well...
- Could I?

424
00:57:26.036 --> 00:57:29.325
Where else but in Grasse!

425
00:57:35.178 --> 00:57:37.585
Within a week, Grenouille was well again.

426
00:57:37.951 --> 00:57:40.729
But in order to travel to Grasse,
and find a job,

427
00:57:40.773 --> 00:57:43.441
he needed a journeyman's papers.

428
00:57:43.688 --> 00:57:45.581
Baldini agreed to provide them,

429
00:57:45.922 --> 00:57:51.873
on condition that Grenouille left him
not less than 100 formulas for new perfumes.

430
00:57:52.707 --> 00:57:56.977
Grenouille did not mind.
He could've given him a thousand.

431
00:58:02.537 --> 00:58:06.606
The morning of Grenouille's departure,
Baldini was pleased.

432
00:58:07.069 --> 00:58:11.178
At last, he felt rewarded
for his many years of hard work.

433
00:58:11.721 --> 00:58:14.937
He could not remember
a happier day.

434
00:58:15.144 --> 00:58:18.066
Deeply satisfied, he went
back to sleep...

435
00:58:18.571 --> 00:58:21.661
and awoke no more
in this life.

436
00:58:40.715 --> 00:58:45.651
With every step Grenouille took away
from the city, the happier he felt.

437
00:58:46.118 --> 00:58:51.033
The air above him grew
clearer, purer, cleaner.

438
00:58:51.168 --> 00:58:54.373
And at last, he was
able to breathe freely.

439
00:58:57.874 --> 00:59:00.573
There were two ways
to reach Grasse.

440
00:59:00.784 --> 00:59:04.446
The first followed the winding road
through the villages...

441
00:59:04.447 --> 00:59:07.582
while the second lay straight across
the hills and mountains,

442
00:59:07.643 --> 00:59:09.842
down into Provence.

443
00:59:10.878 --> 00:59:13.240
The choice was quite easy.

444
00:59:17.122 --> 00:59:22.157
Thus, his nose led him ever higher,
ever further from mankind.

445
00:59:22.577 --> 00:59:28.140
Ever more towards the magnetic pole
of the greatest possible solitude.

446
01:00:06.881 --> 01:00:08.312
Grenouille needed a moment...

447
01:00:08.366 --> 01:00:11.411
to believe that he had actually
found a spot on earth...

448
01:00:11.447 --> 01:00:14.388
where scent was almost absent.

449
01:00:19.604 --> 01:00:20.866
Spread all around...

450
01:00:20.932 --> 01:00:24.143
lay nothing but the tranquil
scent of dead stone.

451
01:00:27.473 --> 01:00:30.683
There was something
sacred about this place.

452
01:00:34.348 --> 01:00:37.065
No longer distracted
by anything external,

453
01:00:37.820 --> 01:00:42.571
he was finally able
to bask in his own existence.

454
01:00:44.044 --> 01:00:47.379
And found it splendid!

455
01:00:54.627 --> 01:00:59.066
After a while, he almost forgot
his plans and obsessions.

456
01:01:00.448 --> 01:01:04.096
And indeed,
might've done so altogether.

457
01:01:19.090 --> 01:01:20.318
Helloá.

458
01:01:24.432 --> 01:01:25.849
Helloá.

459
01:01:28.597 --> 01:01:30.108
Helloá.

460
01:01:47.622 --> 01:01:50.470
There were a thousand smells
in his clothes.

461
01:01:50.535 --> 01:01:53.573
The smell of sand, stone, moss...

462
01:01:53.613 --> 01:01:56.254
even the smell of the sausage
he'd eaten weeks ago.

463
01:01:56.744 --> 01:01:59.220
Only one smell was not there:

464
01:02:02.540 --> 01:02:04.038
His own.

465
01:02:41.083 --> 01:02:43.753
For the first time in his life,
Grenouille realized...

466
01:02:43.815 --> 01:02:46.421
that he had no smell of his own.

467
01:02:47.742 --> 01:02:49.291
He realized that all his life...

468
01:02:49.371 --> 01:02:51.820
he had been a nobody
to everyone.

469
01:02:53.066 --> 01:02:56.902
What he now felt
was the fear of his own oblivion.

470
01:02:57.616 --> 01:02:59.306
It was as though...

471
01:02:59.479 --> 01:03:01.436
he did not exist.

472
01:03:06.837 --> 01:03:11.160
By the first light of next morning,
Grenouille had a new plan.

473
01:03:11.566 --> 01:03:14.499
He must continue
his journey to Grasse.

474
01:03:14.833 --> 01:03:18.375
There he would teach the world
not only that he existed...

475
01:03:18.450 --> 01:03:20.146
that he was someone...

476
01:03:20.488 --> 01:03:23.098
but that he was exceptional.

477
01:03:27.144 --> 01:03:28.865
And with this decision,

478
01:03:29.284 --> 01:03:33.563
it seemed that the gods
had at last begun to smile on him.

479
01:08:01.056 --> 01:08:02.375
Laura?

480
01:08:10.076 --> 01:08:11.363
Laura?

481
01:08:12.174 --> 01:08:14.014
Coming, papa.

482
01:08:50.605 --> 01:08:52.971
Haven't seen you here before.

483
01:08:54.514 --> 01:08:56.255
It's my first season.

484
01:08:57.744 --> 01:08:59.903
Picking together
is always more fun.

485
01:09:01.304 --> 01:09:03.539
They say you pick
everything you find.

486
01:09:48.001 --> 01:09:52.097
Idiot! How many times do I told you
not to cram the blossoms in...

487
01:09:52.135 --> 01:09:53.894
like you're stuffing a chicken?

488
01:09:55.428 --> 01:09:57.195
Watch how Grenouille does it.

489
01:09:59.251 --> 01:10:03.361
Look how skillfully he handles them.
The whole art of Enflourage...

490
01:10:03.401 --> 01:10:07.491
is to allow the flowers to die slowly,
in their sleep as it were...

491
01:10:07.833 --> 01:10:12.789
handle them as you would a lady.
Wouldn't you agree with me, Druot?

492
01:10:13.256 --> 01:10:15.107
If you say so, madame.

493
01:10:17.736 --> 01:10:20.434
You! Check the jonquil blossoms.

494
01:10:23.966 --> 01:10:25.633
It need more time.

495
01:10:28.227 --> 01:10:30.006
Do what I say.

496
01:11:14.202 --> 01:11:15.452
Stop it!

497
01:11:16.387 --> 01:11:17.781
I'm not in the mood.

498
01:11:18.217 --> 01:11:19.455
Are you sure?

499
01:11:20.461 --> 01:11:22.164
Of course I'm sure.

500
01:11:28.479 --> 01:11:30.094
I said...

501
01:11:32.751 --> 01:11:34.241
"no".

